Detailed Description

template<unsigned int friend_Dim, FEFamily friend_T_radial, InfMapType friend_T_map>
class libMesh::InfFE< friend_Dim, friend_T_radial, friend_T_map >

A specific instatiation of the FEBase class. This class is templated, and specific template instantiations will result in different Infinite Element families, similar to the FE class. InfFE builds a FE<Dim-1,T_base>, and most of the requests related to the base are handed over to this object. All methods related to the radial part are collected in the nested class Radial. Similarly, most of the static methods concerning base approximation are contained in Base.

Having different shape approximation families in radial direction introduces the requirement for an additional Order in this class. Therefore, the FEType internals change when infinite elements are enabled. When the specific infinite element type is not known at compile time, use the FEBase::build() member to create abstract (but still optimized) infinite elements at run time.

The node numbering scheme is the one from the current infinite element. Each node in the base holds exactly the same number of dofs as an adjacent conventional FE would contain. The nodes further out hold the additional dof necessary for radial approximation. The order of the outer nodes' components is such that the radial shapes have highest priority, followed by the base shapes.

Author
Daniel Dreyer
Date
2003

Constructor & Destructor Documentation

template<unsigned int Dim, FEFamily T_radial, InfMapType T_map>
libMesh::InfFE< Dim, T_radial, T_map >::InfFE ( const FEType &  fet)
explicit

Constructor. Initializes some data structures. Builds a FE<Dim-1,T_base> object to handle approximation in the base, so that there is no need to template InfFE<Dim,T_radial,T_map> also with respect to the base approximation T_base.

The same remarks concerning compile-time optimization for FE also hold for InfFE. Use the FEBase::build_InfFE(const unsigned int, const FEType&) method to build specific instantiations of InfFE at run time.

Member Function Documentation

template<unsigned int Dim, FEFamily T_radial, InfMapType T_map>
void libMesh::InfFE< Dim, T_radial, T_map >::attach_quadrature_rule ( QBase *  q)
virtual

The use of quadrature rules with the InfFE class is somewhat different from the approach of the FE class. While the FE class requires an appropriately initialized quadrature rule object, and simply uses it, the InfFE class requires only the quadrature rule object of the current FE class. From this QBase*, it determines the necessary data, and builds two appropriate quadrature classes, one for radial, and another for base integration, using the convenient QBase::build() method.

Implements libMesh::FEAbstract.

112  if (Dim != 1)
113  {
114  // build a Dim-1 quadrature rule of the type that we received
115  AutoPtr<QBase> apq( QBase::build(q->type(), qrule_dim-1, base_int_order) );
116  base_qrule = apq.release();
117  base_fe->attach_quadrature_rule(base_qrule);
118  }
119

121  radial_qrule = new QGauss(1, radial_int_order);
122

124  // with which we initialized our own quadrature rules
125  qrule = q;

template<typename T>
static AutoPtr<FEGenericBase> libMesh::FEGenericBase< T >::build ( const unsigned int  dim,
const FEType &  type 
)
staticinherited

Builds a specific finite element type. A AutoPtr<FEGenericBase> is returned to prevent a memory leak. This way the user need not remember to delete the object.

The build call will fail if the OutputType of this class is not compatible with the output required for the requested type

1507  std::abs(ui - Uint(i)) < TOLERANCE);
1508  ui = Uint(i);
1509  // We should be fixing all dofs by now; no need to keep track of
1510  // that unless we're debugging
1511 #ifndef NDEBUG
1512  dof_is_fixed[free_dof[i]] = true;
1513 #endif
1514  }
1515 
1516 #ifndef NDEBUG
1517  // Make sure every DoF got reached!
1518  for (unsigned int i=0; i != new_n_dofs; ++i)
1519  libmesh_assert(dof_is_fixed[i]);
1520 #endif
1521 }

protected

Combines the shape functions, which were formed in init_shape_functions(Elem*), with geometric data. Has to be called every time the geometric configuration changes. Afterwards, the fields are ready to be used to compute global derivatives, the jacobian etc, see FEAbstract::compute_map().

template<unsigned int Dim, FEFamily T_radial, InfMapType T_map>
void libMesh::InfFE< Dim, T_radial, T_map >::compute_data ( const FEType &  fe_t,
const Elem *  inf_elem,
FEComputeData &  data 
)
static

Generalized version of shape(), takes an Elem*. The data contains both input and output parameters. For frequency domain simulations, the complex-valued shape is returned. In time domain both the computed shape, and the phase is returned. Note that the phase (proportional to the distance of the Point data.p from the envelope) is actually a measure how far into the future the results are. Pretty weird, hm!?

staticprotected

Does the same as compute_node_indices(), but stores the maps for the current element type. Provided the infinite element type changes seldom, this is probably faster than using compute_node_indices () alone. This is possible since the number of nodes is not likely to change.

1906  // periodic (and possibly h refinement) constraints:
1907  // constrain dofs shared between
1908  // this element and ones as coarse
1909  // as or coarser than this element.
1910  if (neigh->level() <= elem->level())
1911  {
1912  unsigned int s_neigh =
1913  mesh.get_boundary_info().side_with_boundary_id
1914  (neigh, periodic->pairedboundary);
1915  libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (s_neigh, libMesh::invalid_uint);
1916 
1917 #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_AMR
1918  // Find the minimum p level; we build the h constraint
1919  // matrix with this and then constrain away all higher p
1920  // DoFs.
1921  libmesh_assert(neigh->active());
1922  const unsigned int min_p_level =
1923  std::min(elem->p_level(), neigh->p_level());
1924 
1925  // we may need to make the FE objects reinit with the
1926  // minimum shared p_level
1927  // FIXME - I hate using const_cast<> and avoiding
1928  // accessor functions; there's got to be a
1929  // better way to do this!
1930  const unsigned int old_elem_level = elem->p_level();
1931  if (old_elem_level != min_p_level)
1932  (const_cast<Elem *>(elem))->hack_p_level(min_p_level);
1933  const unsigned int old_neigh_level = neigh->p_level();
1934  if (old_neigh_level != min_p_level)
1935  (const_cast<Elem *>(neigh))->hack_p_level(min_p_level);
1936 #endif // #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_AMR
1937 
1938  // We can do a projection with a single integration,
1939  // due to the assumption of nested finite element
1940  // subspaces.
1941  // FIXME: it might be more efficient to do nodes,
1942  // then edges, then side, to reduce the size of the
1943  // Cholesky factorization(s)
1944  my_fe->reinit(elem, s);
1945 
1946  dof_map.dof_indices (elem, my_dof_indices,
1947  variable_number);
1948  dof_map.dof_indices (neigh, neigh_dof_indices,
1949  variable_number);
1950 
1951  const unsigned int n_qp = my_qface.n_points();
1952 
1953  // Translate the quadrature points over to the
1954  // neighbor's boundary
1955  std::vector<Point> neigh_point(q_point.size());
1956  for (unsigned int i=0; i != neigh_point.size(); ++i)
1957  neigh_point[i] = periodic->get_corresponding_pos(q_point[i]);
1958 
1959  FEInterface::inverse_map (Dim, base_fe_type, neigh,
1960  neigh_point, neigh_qface);
1961 
1962  neigh_fe->reinit(neigh, &neigh_qface);
1963 
1964  // We're only concerned with DOFs whose values (and/or first
1965  // derivatives for C1 elements) are supported on side nodes
1966  FEInterface::dofs_on_side(elem, Dim, base_fe_type, s, my_side_dofs);
1967  FEInterface::dofs_on_side(neigh, Dim, base_fe_type, s_neigh, neigh_side_dofs);
1968 
1969  // We're done with functions that examine Elem::p_level(),
1970  // so let's unhack those levels
1971 #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_AMR
1972  if (elem->p_level() != old_elem_level)
1973  (const_cast<Elem *>(elem))->hack_p_level(old_elem_level);
1974  if (neigh->p_level() != old_neigh_level)
1975  (const_cast<Elem *>(neigh))->hack_p_level(old_neigh_level);
1976 #endif // #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_AMR
1977 
1978  const unsigned int n_side_dofs =
1979  cast_int<unsigned int>
1980  (my_side_dofs.size());
1981  libmesh_assert_equal_to (n_side_dofs, neigh_side_dofs.size());
1982 
1983  Ke.resize (n_side_dofs, n_side_dofs);
1984  Ue.resize(n_side_dofs);
1985 
1986  // Form the projection matrix, (inner product of fine basis
1987  // functions against fine test functions)
1988  for (unsigned int is = 0; is != n_side_dofs; ++is)
1989  {
1990  const unsigned int i = my_side_dofs[is];
1991  for (unsigned int js = 0; js != n_side_dofs; ++js)
1992  {
1993  const unsigned int j = my_side_dofs[js];
1994  for (unsigned int qp = 0; qp != n_qp; ++qp)
1995  {
1996  Ke(is,js) += JxW[qp] *
1997  TensorTools::inner_product(phi[i][qp],
1998  phi[j][qp]);
1999  if (cont != C_ZERO)
2000  Ke(is,js) += JxW[qp] *
2001  TensorTools::inner_product((*dphi)[i][qp] *
2002  (*face_normals)[qp],
2003  (*dphi)[j][qp] *
2004  (*face_normals)[qp]);
2005  }
2006  }
2007  }
2008 
2009  // Form the right hand sides, (inner product of coarse basis
2010  // functions against fine test functions)
2011  for (unsigned int is = 0; is != n_side_dofs; ++is)
2012  {
2013  const unsigned int i = neigh_side_dofs[is];
2014  Fe.resize (n_side_dofs);
2015  for (unsigned int js = 0; js != n_side_dofs; ++js)
2016  {
2017  const unsigned int j = my_side_dofs[js];
2018  for (unsigned int qp = 0; qp != n_qp; ++qp)
2019  {
2020  Fe(js) += JxW[qp] *
2021  TensorTools::inner_product(neigh_phi[i][qp],
2022  phi[j][qp]);
2023  if (cont != C_ZERO)
2024  Fe(js) += JxW[qp] *
2025  TensorTools::inner_product((*neigh_dphi)[i][qp] *
2026  (*face_normals)[qp],
2027  (*dphi)[j][qp] *
2028  (*face_normals)[qp]);
2029  }
2030  }
2031  Ke.cholesky_solve(Fe, Ue[is]);
2032  }
2033 
2034  // Make sure we're not adding recursive constraints
2035  // due to the redundancy in the way we add periodic
2036  // boundary constraints
2037  //
2038  // In order for this to work while threaded or on
2039  // distributed meshes, we need a rigorous way to
2040  // avoid recursive constraints. Here it is:
2041  //
2042  // For vertex DoFs, if there is a "prior" element
2043  // (i.e. a coarser element or an equally refined
2044  // element with a lower id) on this boundary which
2045  // contains the vertex point, then we will avoid
2046  // generating constraints; the prior element (or
2047  // something prior to it) may do so. If we are the
2048  // most prior (or "primary") element on this
2049  // boundary sharing this point, then we look at the
2050  // boundary periodic to us, we find the primary
2051  // element there, and if that primary is coarser or
2052  // equal-but-lower-id, then our vertex dofs are
2053  // constrained in terms of that element.
2054  //
2055  // For edge DoFs, if there is a coarser element
2056  // on this boundary sharing this edge, then we will
2057  // avoid generating constraints (we will be
2058  // constrained indirectly via AMR constraints
2059  // connecting us to the coarser element's DoFs). If
2060  // we are the coarsest element sharing this edge,
2061  // then we generate constraints if and only if we
2062  // are finer than the coarsest element on the
2063  // boundary periodic to us sharing the corresponding
2064  // periodic edge, or if we are at equal level but
2065  // our edge nodes have higher ids than the periodic
2066  // edge nodes (sorted from highest to lowest, then
2067  // compared lexicographically)
2068  //
2069  // For face DoFs, we generate constraints if we are
2070  // finer than our periodic neighbor, or if we are at
2071  // equal level but our element id is higher than its
2072  // element id.
2073  //
2074  // If the primary neighbor is also the current elem
2075  // (a 1-element-thick mesh) then we choose which
2076  // vertex dofs to constrain via lexicographic
2077  // ordering on point locations
2078 
2079  // FIXME: This code doesn't yet properly handle
2080  // cases where multiple different periodic BCs
2081  // intersect.
2082  std::set<dof_id_type> my_constrained_dofs;
2083 
2084  for (unsigned int n = 0; n != elem->n_nodes(); ++n)
2085  {
2086  if (!elem->is_node_on_side(n,s))
2087  continue;
2088 
2089  const Node* my_node = elem->get_node(n);
2090 
2091  if (elem->is_vertex(n))
2092  {
2093  // Find all boundary ids that include this
2094  // point and have periodic boundary
2095  // conditions for this variable
2096  std::set<boundary_id_type> point_bcids;
2097 
2098  for (unsigned int new_s = 0; new_s !=
2099  elem->n_sides(); ++new_s)
2100  {
2101  if (!elem->is_node_on_side(n,new_s))
2102  continue;
2103 
2104  const std::vector<boundary_id_type> new_bc_ids =
2105  mesh.get_boundary_info().boundary_ids (elem, s);
2106  for (std::vector<boundary_id_type>::const_iterator
2107  new_id_it=new_bc_ids.begin(); new_id_it!=new_bc_ids.end(); ++new_id_it)
2108  {
2109  const boundary_id_type new_boundary_id = *new_id_it;
2110  const PeriodicBoundaryBase *new_periodic = boundaries.boundary(new_boundary_id);
2111  if (new_periodic && new_periodic->is_my_variable(variable_number))
2112  {
2113  point_bcids.insert(new_boundary_id);
2114  }
2115  }
2116  }
2117 
2118  // See if this vertex has point neighbors to
2119  // defer to
2120  if (primary_boundary_point_neighbor
2121  (elem, *my_node, mesh.get_boundary_info(), point_bcids)
2122  != elem)
2123  continue;
2124 
2125  // Find the complementary boundary id set
2126  std::set<boundary_id_type> point_pairedids;
2127  for (std::set<boundary_id_type>::const_iterator i =
2128  point_bcids.begin(); i != point_bcids.end(); ++i)
2129  {
2130  const boundary_id_type new_boundary_id = *i;
2131  const PeriodicBoundaryBase *new_periodic = boundaries.boundary(new_boundary_id);
2132  point_pairedids.insert(new_periodic->pairedboundary);
2133  }
2134 
2135  // What do we want to constrain against?
2136  const Elem* primary_elem = NULL;
2137  const Elem* main_neigh = NULL;
2138  Point main_pt = *my_node,
2139  primary_pt = *my_node;
2140 
2141  for (std::set<boundary_id_type>::const_iterator i =
2142  point_bcids.begin(); i != point_bcids.end(); ++i)
2143  {
2144  // Find the corresponding periodic point and
2145  // its primary neighbor
2146  const boundary_id_type new_boundary_id = *i;
2147  const PeriodicBoundaryBase *new_periodic = boundaries.boundary(new_boundary_id);
2148 
2149  const Point neigh_pt =
2150  new_periodic->get_corresponding_pos(*my_node);
2151 
2152  // If the point is getting constrained
2153  // to itself by this PBC then we don't
2154  // generate any constraints
2155  if (neigh_pt.absolute_fuzzy_equals
2156  (*my_node, primary_hmin*TOLERANCE))
2157  continue;
2158 
2159  // Otherwise we'll have a constraint in
2160  // one direction or another
2161  if (!primary_elem)
2162  primary_elem = elem;
2163 
2164  const Elem *primary_neigh =
2165  primary_boundary_point_neighbor
2166  (neigh, neigh_pt,
2167  mesh.get_boundary_info(),
2168  point_pairedids);
2169 
2170  libmesh_assert(primary_neigh);
2171 
2172  if (new_boundary_id == boundary_id)
2173  {
2174  main_neigh = primary_neigh;
2175  main_pt = neigh_pt;
2176  }
2177 
2178  // Finer elements will get constrained in
2179  // terms of coarser neighbors, not the
2180  // other way around
2181  if ((primary_neigh->level() > primary_elem->level()) ||
2182 
2183  // For equal-level elements, the one with
2184  // higher id gets constrained in terms of
2185  // the one with lower id
2186  (primary_neigh->level() == primary_elem->level() &&
2187  primary_neigh->id() > primary_elem->id()) ||
2188 
2189  // On a one-element-thick mesh, we compare
2190  // points to see what side gets constrained
2191  (primary_neigh == primary_elem &&
2192  (neigh_pt > primary_pt)))
2193  continue;
2194 
2195  primary_elem = primary_neigh;
2196  primary_pt = neigh_pt;
2197  }
2198 
2199  if (!primary_elem ||
2200  primary_elem != main_neigh ||
2201  primary_pt != main_pt)
2202  continue;
2203  }
2204  else if (elem->is_edge(n))
2205  {
2206  // Find which edge we're on
2207  unsigned int e=0;
2208  for (; e != elem->n_edges(); ++e)
2209  {
2210  if (elem->is_node_on_edge(n,e))
2211  break;
2212  }
2213  libmesh_assert_less (e, elem->n_edges());
2214 
2215  // Find the edge end nodes
2216  Node *e1 = NULL,
2217  *e2 = NULL;
2218  for (unsigned int nn = 0; nn != elem->n_nodes(); ++nn)
2219  {
2220  if (nn == n)
2221  continue;
2222 
2223  if (elem->is_node_on_edge(nn, e))
2224  {
2225  if (e1 == NULL)
2226  {
2227  e1 = elem->get_node(nn);
2228  }
2229  else
2230  {
2231  e2 = elem->get_node(nn);
2232  break;
2233  }
2234  }
2235  }
2236  libmesh_assert (e1 && e2);
2237 
2238  // Find all boundary ids that include this
2239  // edge and have periodic boundary
2240  // conditions for this variable
2241  std::set<boundary_id_type> edge_bcids;
2242 
2243  for (unsigned int new_s = 0; new_s !=
2244  elem->n_sides(); ++new_s)
2245  {
2246  if (!elem->is_node_on_side(n,new_s))
2247  continue;
2248 
2249  const std::vector<boundary_id_type>& new_bc_ids =
2250  mesh.get_boundary_info().boundary_ids (elem, s);
2251  for (std::vector<boundary_id_type>::const_iterator
2252  new_id_it=new_bc_ids.begin(); new_id_it!=new_bc_ids.end(); ++new_id_it)
2253  {
2254  const boundary_id_type new_boundary_id = *new_id_it;
2255  const PeriodicBoundaryBase *new_periodic = boundaries.boundary(new_boundary_id);
2256  if (new_periodic && new_periodic->is_my_variable(variable_number))
2257  {
2258  edge_bcids.insert(new_boundary_id);
2259  }
2260  }
2261  }
2262 
2263 
2264  // See if this edge has neighbors to defer to
2265  if (primary_boundary_edge_neighbor
2266  (elem, *e1, *e2, mesh.get_boundary_info(), edge_bcids)
2267  != elem)
2268  continue;
2269 
2270  // Find the complementary boundary id set
2271  std::set<boundary_id_type> edge_pairedids;
2272  for (std::set<boundary_id_type>::const_iterator i =
2273  edge_bcids.begin(); i != edge_bcids.end(); ++i)
2274  {
2275  const boundary_id_type new_boundary_id = *i;
2276  const PeriodicBoundaryBase *new_periodic = boundaries.boundary(new_boundary_id);
2277  edge_pairedids.insert(new_periodic->pairedboundary);
2278  }
2279 
2280  // What do we want to constrain against?
2281  const Elem* primary_elem = NULL;
2282  const Elem* main_neigh = NULL;
2283  Point main_pt1 = *e1,
2284  main_pt2 = *e2,
2285  primary_pt1 = *e1,
2286  primary_pt2 = *e2;
2287 
2288  for (std::set<boundary_id_type>::const_iterator i =
2289  edge_bcids.begin(); i != edge_bcids.end(); ++i)
2290  {
2291  // Find the corresponding periodic edge and
2292  // its primary neighbor
2293  const boundary_id_type new_boundary_id = *i;
2294  const PeriodicBoundaryBase *new_periodic = boundaries.boundary(new_boundary_id);
2295 
2296  Point neigh_pt1 = new_periodic->get_corresponding_pos(*e1),
2297  neigh_pt2 = new_periodic->get_corresponding_pos(*e2);
2298 
2299  // If the edge is getting constrained
2300  // to itself by this PBC then we don't
2301  // generate any constraints
2302  if (neigh_pt1.absolute_fuzzy_equals
2303  (*e1, primary_hmin*TOLERANCE) &&
2304  neigh_pt2.absolute_fuzzy_equals
2305  (*e2, primary_hmin*TOLERANCE))
2306  continue;
2307 
2308  // Otherwise we'll have a constraint in
2309  // one direction or another
2310  if (!primary_elem)
2311  primary_elem = elem;
2312 
2313  const Elem *primary_neigh = primary_boundary_edge_neighbor
2314  (neigh, neigh_pt1, neigh_pt2,
2315  mesh.get_boundary_info(), edge_pairedids);
2316 
2317  libmesh_assert(primary_neigh);
2318 
2319  if (new_boundary_id == boundary_id)
2320  {
2321  main_neigh = primary_neigh;
2322  main_pt1 = neigh_pt1;
2323  main_pt2 = neigh_pt2;
2324  }
2325 
2326  // If we have a one-element thick mesh,
2327  // we'll need to sort our points to get a
2328  // consistent ordering rule
2329  //
2330  // Use >= in this test to make sure that,
2331  // for angular constraints, no node gets
2332  // constrained to itself.
2333  if (primary_neigh == primary_elem)
2334  {
2335  if (primary_pt1 > primary_pt2)
2336  std::swap(primary_pt1, primary_pt2);
2337  if (neigh_pt1 > neigh_pt2)
2338  std::swap(neigh_pt1, neigh_pt2);
2339 
2340  if (neigh_pt2 >= primary_pt2)
2341  continue;
2342  }
2343 
2344  // Otherwise:
2345  // Finer elements will get constrained in
2346  // terms of coarser ones, not the other way
2347  // around
2348  if ((primary_neigh->level() > primary_elem->level()) ||
2349 
2350  // For equal-level elements, the one with
2351  // higher id gets constrained in terms of
2352  // the one with lower id
2353  (primary_neigh->level() == primary_elem->level() &&
2354  primary_neigh->id() > primary_elem->id()))
2355  continue;
2356 
2357  primary_elem = primary_neigh;
2358  primary_pt1 = neigh_pt1;
2359  primary_pt2 = neigh_pt2;
2360  }
2361 
2362  if (!primary_elem ||
2363  primary_elem != main_neigh ||
2364  primary_pt1 != main_pt1 ||
2365  primary_pt2 != main_pt2)
2366  continue;
2367  }
2368  else if (elem->is_face(n))
2369  {
2370  // If we have a one-element thick mesh,
2371  // use the ordering of the face node and its
2372  // periodic counterpart to determine what
2373  // gets constrained
2374  if (neigh == elem)
2375  {
2376  const Point neigh_pt =
2377  periodic->get_corresponding_pos(*my_node);
2378  if (neigh_pt > *my_node)
2379  continue;
2380  }
2381 
2382  // Otherwise:
2383  // Finer elements will get constrained in
2384  // terms of coarser ones, not the other way
2385  // around
2386  if ((neigh->level() > elem->level()) ||
2387 
2388  // For equal-level elements, the one with
2389  // higher id gets constrained in terms of
2390  // the one with lower id
2391  (neigh->level() == elem->level() &&
2392  neigh->id() > elem->id()))
2393  continue;
2394  }
2395 
2396  // If we made it here without hitting a continue
2397  // statement, then we're at a node whose dofs
2398  // should be constrained by this element's
2399  // calculations.
2400  const unsigned int n_comp =
2401  my_node->n_comp(sys_number, variable_number);
2402 
2403  for (unsigned int i=0; i != n_comp; ++i)
2404  my_constrained_dofs.insert
2405  (my_node->dof_number
2406  (sys_number, variable_number, i));
2407  }
2408 
2409  // FIXME: old code for disambiguating periodic BCs:
2410  // this is not threadsafe nor safe to run on a
2411  // non-serialized mesh.
2412  /*
2413  std::vector<bool> recursive_constraint(n_side_dofs, false);

2418  const dof_id_type their_dof_g = neigh_dof_indices[i];

2442 
2443  for (unsigned int js = 0; js != n_side_dofs; ++js)

2446  // if (recursive_constraint[js])
2447  // continue;
2448

2450  const dof_id_type my_dof_g = my_dof_indices[j];
2451  libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (my_dof_g, DofObject::invalid_id);
2452

2455  continue;
2456

2458 
2459  // we may be running constraint methods concurretly
2460  // on multiple threads, so we need a lock to
2461  // ensure that this constraint is "ours"
2462  {
2463  Threads::spin_mutex::scoped_lock lock(Threads::spin_mtx);
2464 
2465  if (dof_map.is_constrained_dof(my_dof_g))
2466  continue;
2467 
2468  constraint_row = &(constraints[my_dof_g]);
2469  libmesh_assert(constraint_row->empty());
2470  }
2471 
2472  for (unsigned int is = 0; is != n_side_dofs; ++is)
2473  {
2474  const unsigned int i = neigh_side_dofs[is];
2475  const dof_id_type their_dof_g = neigh_dof_indices[i];
2476  libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (their_dof_g, DofObject::invalid_id);
2477 
2478  // Periodic constraints should never be
2479  // self-constraints
2480  // libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (their_dof_g, my_dof_g);
2481 
2482  const Real their_dof_value = Ue[is](js);
2483 
2484  if (their_dof_g == my_dof_g)
2485  {
2486  libmesh_assert_less (std::abs(their_dof_value-1.), 1.e-5);
2487  for (unsigned int k = 0; k != n_side_dofs; ++k)
2488  libmesh_assert(k == is || std::abs(Ue[k](js)) < 1.e-5);
2489  continue;
2490  }
2491 
2492  if (std::abs(their_dof_value) < 10*TOLERANCE)
2493  continue;
2494 
2495  constraint_row->insert(std::make_pair(their_dof_g,
2496  their_dof_value));
2497  }
2498  }
2499  }
2500  // p refinement constraints:
2501  // constrain dofs shared between
2502  // active elements and neighbors with
2503  // lower polynomial degrees
2504 #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_AMR
2505  const unsigned int min_p_level =
2506  neigh->min_p_level_by_neighbor(elem, elem->p_level());
2507  if (min_p_level < elem->p_level())
2508  {
2509  // Adaptive p refinement of non-hierarchic bases will
2510  // require more coding
2511  libmesh_assert(my_fe->is_hierarchic());
2512  dof_map.constrain_p_dofs(variable_number, elem,
2513  s, min_p_level);
2514  }
2515 #endif // #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_AMR

1663  const unsigned int n_side_dofs =
1664  cast_int<unsigned int>(my_side_dofs.size());
1665  libmesh_assert_equal_to (n_side_dofs, neigh_side_dofs.size());
1666 
1667  Ke.resize (n_side_dofs, n_side_dofs);
1668  Ue.resize(n_side_dofs);
1669 
1670  // Form the projection matrix, (inner product of fine basis
1671  // functions against fine test functions)
1672  for (unsigned int is = 0; is != n_side_dofs; ++is)
1673  {
1674  const unsigned int i = my_side_dofs[is];
1675  for (unsigned int js = 0; js != n_side_dofs; ++js)
1676  {
1677  const unsigned int j = my_side_dofs[js];
1678  for (unsigned int qp = 0; qp != n_qp; ++qp)
1679  {
1680  Ke(is,js) += JxW[qp] * TensorTools::inner_product(phi[i][qp], phi[j][qp]);
1681  if (cont != C_ZERO)
1682  Ke(is,js) += JxW[qp] *
1683  TensorTools::inner_product((*dphi)[i][qp] *
1684  (*face_normals)[qp],
1685  (*dphi)[j][qp] *
1686  (*face_normals)[qp]);
1687  }
1688  }
1689  }
1690 
1691  // Form the right hand sides, (inner product of coarse basis
1692  // functions against fine test functions)
1693  for (unsigned int is = 0; is != n_side_dofs; ++is)
1694  {
1695  const unsigned int i = neigh_side_dofs[is];
1696  Fe.resize (n_side_dofs);
1697  for (unsigned int js = 0; js != n_side_dofs; ++js)
1698  {
1699  const unsigned int j = my_side_dofs[js];
1700  for (unsigned int qp = 0; qp != n_qp; ++qp)
1701  {
1702  Fe(js) += JxW[qp] *
1703  TensorTools::inner_product(neigh_phi[i][qp],
1704  phi[j][qp]);
1705  if (cont != C_ZERO)
1706  Fe(js) += JxW[qp] *
1707  TensorTools::inner_product((*neigh_dphi)[i][qp] *
1708  (*face_normals)[qp],
1709  (*dphi)[j][qp] *
1710  (*face_normals)[qp]);
1711  }
1712  }
1713  Ke.cholesky_solve(Fe, Ue[is]);
1714  }
1715 
1716  for (unsigned int js = 0; js != n_side_dofs; ++js)
1717  {
1718  const unsigned int j = my_side_dofs[js];
1719  const dof_id_type my_dof_g = my_dof_indices[j];
1720  libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (my_dof_g, DofObject::invalid_id);
1721 
1722  // Hunt for "constraining against myself" cases before
1723  // we bother creating a constraint row
1724  bool self_constraint = false;
1725  for (unsigned int is = 0; is != n_side_dofs; ++is)
1726  {
1727  const unsigned int i = neigh_side_dofs[is];
1728  const dof_id_type their_dof_g = neigh_dof_indices[i];
1729  libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (their_dof_g, DofObject::invalid_id);
1730 
1731  if (their_dof_g == my_dof_g)
1732  {
1733 #ifndef NDEBUG
1734  const Real their_dof_value = Ue[is](js);
1735  libmesh_assert_less (std::abs(their_dof_value-1.),
1736  10*TOLERANCE);
1737 
1738  for (unsigned int k = 0; k != n_side_dofs; ++k)
1739  libmesh_assert(k == is ||
1740  std::abs(Ue[k](js)) <
1741  10*TOLERANCE);
1742 #endif
1743 
1744  self_constraint = true;
1745  break;
1746  }
1747  }
1748 
1749  if (self_constraint)
1750  continue;
1751 
1752  DofConstraintRow* constraint_row;
1753 
1754  // we may be running constraint methods concurrently
1755  // on multiple threads, so we need a lock to
1756  // ensure that this constraint is "ours"
1757  {
1758  Threads::spin_mutex::scoped_lock lock(Threads::spin_mtx);
1759 
1760  if (dof_map.is_constrained_dof(my_dof_g))
1761  continue;
1762 
1763  constraint_row = &(constraints[my_dof_g]);
1764  libmesh_assert(constraint_row->empty());
1765  }
1766 
1767  for (unsigned int is = 0; is != n_side_dofs; ++is)
1768  {
1769  const unsigned int i = neigh_side_dofs[is];
1770  const dof_id_type their_dof_g = neigh_dof_indices[i];
1771  libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (their_dof_g, DofObject::invalid_id);
1772  libmesh_assert_not_equal_to (their_dof_g, my_dof_g);
1773 
1774  const Real their_dof_value = Ue[is](js);
1775 
1776  if (std::abs(their_dof_value) < 10*TOLERANCE)
1777  continue;
1778 
1779  constraint_row->insert(std::make_pair(their_dof_g,
1780  their_dof_value));
1781  }
1782  }
1783  }
1784  // p refinement constraints:
1785  // constrain dofs shared between
1786  // active elements and neighbors with
1787  // lower polynomial degrees
1788  const unsigned int min_p_level =
1789  neigh->min_p_level_by_neighbor(elem, elem->p_level());
1790  if (min_p_level < elem->p_level())
1791  {
1792  // Adaptive p refinement of non-hierarchic bases will
1793  // require more coding
1794  libmesh_assert(my_fe->is_hierarchic());
1795  dof_map.constrain_p_dofs(variable_number, elem,
1796  s, min_p_level);
1797  }
1798  }
1799 }

template<unsigned int Dim, FEFamily T_radial, InfMapType T_map>
void libMesh::InfFE< Dim, T_radial, T_map >::compute_shape_functions ( const Elem *  ,
const std::vector< Point > &   
)
protectedvirtual

After having updated the jacobian and the transformation from local to global coordinates in FEAbstract::compute_map(), the first derivatives of the shape functions are transformed to global coordinates, giving dphi, dphidx/y/z, dphasedx/y/z, dweight. This method should barely be re-defined in derived classes, but still should be usable for children. Therefore, keep it protected. Overloaded method from the FEBase version.

Reimplemented from libMesh::FEGenericBase< T >.

Computes the indices of shape functions in the base base_shape and in radial direction radial_shape (0 in the base, further out) associated to the shape with global index i of an infinite element of type inf_elem_type.

708  /*
709  * An example is provided: the numbers in comments refer to
710  * a fictitious InfHex18. The numbers are chosen as exemplary
711  * values. There is currently no base approximation that
712  * requires this many dof's at nodes, sides, faces and in the element.
713  *
714  * the order of the shape functions is heavily related with the
715  * order the dofs are assigned in \p DofMap::distributed_dofs().
716  * Due to the infinite elements with higher-order base approximation,
717  * some more effort is necessary.
718  *
719  * numbering scheme:
720  * 1. all vertices in the base, assign node->n_comp() dofs to each vertex
721  * 2. all vertices further out: innermost loop: radial shapes,
722  * then the base approximation shapes
723  * 3. all side nodes in the base, assign node->n_comp() dofs to each side node
724  * 4. all side nodes further out: innermost loop: radial shapes,
725  * then the base approximation shapes
726  * 5. (all) face nodes in the base, assign node->n_comp() dofs to each face node
727  * 6. (all) face nodes further out: innermost loop: radial shapes,
728  * then the base approximation shapes
729  * 7. element-associated dof in the base
730  * 8. element-associated dof further out
731  */

840  // these are the limits describing the intervals where the shape function lies
841  const unsigned int n_dof_at_base_vertices = n_base_vertices*n_base_vertex_dof; // 8
842  const unsigned int n_dof_at_all_vertices = n_dof_at_base_vertices*radial_order_p_one; // 40
843 
844  const unsigned int n_dof_at_base_sides = n_base_side_nodes*n_base_side_dof; // 12
845  const unsigned int n_dof_at_all_sides = n_dof_at_base_sides*radial_order_p_one; // 60
846 
847  const unsigned int n_dof_at_base_face = n_base_face_nodes*n_base_face_dof; // 5
848  const unsigned int n_dof_at_all_faces = n_dof_at_base_face*radial_order_p_one; // 25
849 
850 
851  // start locating the shape function
852  if (i < n_dof_at_base_vertices) // range of i: 0..7
853  {
854  // belongs to vertex in the base
855  radial_shape = 0;
856  base_shape = i;
857  }
858 
859  else if (i < n_dof_at_all_vertices) // range of i: 8..39
860  {
861  /* belongs to vertex in the outer shell
862  *
863  * subtract the number of dof already counted,
864  * so that i_offset contains only the offset for the base
865  */
866  const unsigned int i_offset = i - n_dof_at_base_vertices; // 0..31
867 
868  // first the radial dof are counted, then the base dof
869  radial_shape = (i_offset % radial_order) + 1;
870  base_shape = i_offset / radial_order;
871  }
872 
873  else if (i < n_dof_at_all_vertices+n_dof_at_base_sides) // range of i: 40..51
874  {
875  // belongs to base, is a side node
876  radial_shape = 0;
877  base_shape = i - radial_order * n_dof_at_base_vertices; // 8..19
878  }
879 
880  else if (i < n_dof_at_all_vertices+n_dof_at_all_sides) // range of i: 52..99
881  {
882  // belongs to side node in the outer shell
883  const unsigned int i_offset = i - (n_dof_at_all_vertices
884  + n_dof_at_base_sides); // 0..47
885  radial_shape = (i_offset % radial_order) + 1;
886  base_shape = (i_offset / radial_order) + n_dof_at_base_vertices;
887  }
888 
889  else if (i < n_dof_at_all_vertices+n_dof_at_all_sides+n_dof_at_base_face) // range of i: 100..104
890  {
891  // belongs to the node in the base face
892  radial_shape = 0;
893  base_shape = i - radial_order*(n_dof_at_base_vertices
894  + n_dof_at_base_sides); // 20..24
895  }
896 
897  else if (i < n_dof_at_all_vertices+n_dof_at_all_sides+n_dof_at_all_faces) // range of i: 105..124
898  {
899  // belongs to the node in the outer face
900  const unsigned int i_offset = i - (n_dof_at_all_vertices
901  + n_dof_at_all_sides
902  + n_dof_at_base_face); // 0..19
903  radial_shape = (i_offset % radial_order) + 1;
904  base_shape = (i_offset / radial_order) + n_dof_at_base_vertices + n_dof_at_base_sides;
905  }
906 
907  else if (i < n_dof_at_all_vertices+n_dof_at_all_sides+n_dof_at_all_faces+n_base_elem_dof) // range of i: 125..133
908  {
909  // belongs to the base and is an element associated shape
910  radial_shape = 0;
911  base_shape = i - (n_dof_at_all_vertices
912  + n_dof_at_all_sides
913  + n_dof_at_all_faces); // 0..8
914  }
915 
916  else // range of i: 134..169
917  {
918  libmesh_assert_less (i, n_dofs(fet, inf_elem_type));
919  // belongs to the outer shell and is an element associated shape
920  const unsigned int i_offset = i - (n_dof_at_all_vertices
921  + n_dof_at_all_sides
922  + n_dof_at_all_faces
923  + n_base_elem_dof); // 0..19
924  radial_shape = (i_offset % radial_order) + 1;
925  base_shape = (i_offset / radial_order) + n_dof_at_base_vertices + n_dof_at_base_sides + n_dof_at_base_face;
926  }
927  }
928 
929  return;
930 }

template<unsigned int friend_Dim, FEFamily friend_T_radial, InfMapType friend_T_map>
static Real libMesh::InfFE< friend_Dim, friend_T_radial, friend_T_map >::eval ( Real  v,
Order  o_radial,
unsigned int  i 
)
staticprotected
Returns
the value of the polynomial evaluated at v. This method provides the approximation in radial direction for the overall shape functions, which is defined in InfFE::shape(). This method is allowed to be static, since it is independent of dimension and base_family. It is templated, though, w.r.t. to radial FEFamily.

Specialized for T_radial=INFINITE_MAP, this function returns the value of the mapping shape function in radial direction evaluated at v. Currently, only one specific mapping shape is used. Namely the one by Marques JMMC, Owen DRJ: Infinite elements in quasi-static materially nonlinear problems, Computers and Structures, 1984.

Referenced by libMesh::InfFE< friend_Dim, friend_T_radial, friend_T_map >::compute_data(), libMesh::InfFE< friend_Dim, friend_T_radial, friend_T_map >::init_radial_shape_functions(), libMesh::InfFE< friend_Dim, friend_T_radial, friend_T_map >::inverse_map(), and libMesh::InfFE< friend_Dim, friend_T_radial, friend_T_map >::shape().

template<typename T>
const std::vector<OutputGradient>& libMesh::FEGenericBase< T >::get_dphase ( ) const
inlineinherited
Returns
the global first derivative of the phase term which is used in infinite elements, evaluated at the quadrature points.

In case of the general finite element class FE this field is initialized to all zero, so that the variational formulation for an infinite element returns correct element matrices for a mesh using both finite and infinite elements.

Definition: fe_base.h:633
template<typename T>
const std::vector<Real>& libMesh::FEGenericBase< T >::get_Sobolev_weight ( ) const
inlineinherited
Returns
the multiplicative weight at each quadrature point. This weight is used for certain infinite element weak formulations, so that weighted Sobolev spaces are used for the trial function space. This renders the variational form easily computable.

In case of the general finite element class FE this field is initialized to all ones, so that the variational formulation for an infinite element returns correct element matrices for a mesh using both finite and infinite elements.

212  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& d2psidxi2_map = this->_fe_map->get_d2psidxi2();
213  psi_map.resize (n_total_mapping_shape_functions);
214  dpsidxi_map.resize (n_total_mapping_shape_functions);
215  d2psidxi2_map.resize (n_total_mapping_shape_functions);
216 
217  // if (Dim == 3)
218  {
219  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& dpsideta_map = this->_fe_map->get_dpsideta();
220  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& d2psidxideta_map = this->_fe_map->get_d2psidxideta();
221  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& d2psideta2_map = this->_fe_map->get_d2psideta2();
222  dpsideta_map.resize (n_total_mapping_shape_functions);
223  d2psidxideta_map.resize (n_total_mapping_shape_functions);
224  d2psideta2_map.resize (n_total_mapping_shape_functions);
225  }
226 
227  for (unsigned int i=0; i<n_total_mapping_shape_functions; i++)
228  {
229  psi_map[i].resize (n_total_qp);
230  dpsidxi_map[i].resize (n_total_qp);
231  d2psidxi2_map[i].resize (n_total_qp);
232 
233  // if (Dim == 3)
234  {
235  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& dpsideta_map = this->_fe_map->get_dpsideta();
236  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& d2psidxideta_map = this->_fe_map->get_d2psidxideta();
237  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& d2psideta2_map = this->_fe_map->get_d2psideta2();
238  dpsideta_map[i].resize (n_total_qp);
239  d2psidxideta_map[i].resize (n_total_qp);
240  d2psideta2_map[i].resize (n_total_qp);
241  }
242  }
243  }
244 
245 
246  // compute shape maps
247  {
248  const std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& S_map = (base_fe->get_fe_map()).get_phi_map();
249  const std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& Ss_map = (base_fe->get_fe_map()).get_dphidxi_map();
250 
251  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& psi_map = this->_fe_map->get_psi();
252  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& dpsidxi_map = this->_fe_map->get_dpsidxi();
253  std::vector<std::vector<Real> >& dpsideta_map = this->_fe_map->get_dpsideta();
254 
255  for (unsigned int rp=0; rp<n_radial_qp; rp++) // over radial qp's
256  for (unsigned int bp=0; bp<n_base_qp; bp++) // over base qp's
257  for (unsigned int ti=0; ti<n_total_mapping_shape_functions; ti++) // over all mapping shapes
258  {
259  // let the index vectors take care of selecting the appropriate base/radial mapping shape
260  const unsigned int bi = _base_node_index [ti];
261  const unsigned int ri = _radial_node_index[ti];
262  psi_map [ti][bp+rp*n_base_qp] = S_map [bi][bp] * radial_map [ri][rp];
263  dpsidxi_map [ti][bp+rp*n_base_qp] = Ss_map[bi][bp] * radial_map [ri][rp];
264  dpsideta_map [ti][bp+rp*n_base_qp] = S_map [bi][bp] * dradialdv_map[ri][rp];
265 
266  // second derivatives are not implemented for infinite elements
267  // d2psidxi2_map [ti][bp+rp*n_base_qp] = 0.;
268  // d2psidxideta_map [ti][bp+rp*n_base_qp] = 0.;
269  // d2psideta2_map [ti][bp+rp*n_base_qp] = 0.;
270  }
271 
272  }
273 
274  }
275 
276  // quadrature rule weights
277  {
278  const std::vector<Real>& radial_qw = radial_qrule->get_weights();
279  const std::vector<Real>& base_qw = base_qrule->get_weights();
280 
281  libmesh_assert_equal_to (radial_qw.size(), n_radial_qp);
282  libmesh_assert_equal_to (base_qw.size(), n_base_qp);
283 
284  for (unsigned int rp=0; rp<n_radial_qp; rp++)
285  for (unsigned int bp=0; bp<n_base_qp; bp++)
286  {
287  _total_qrule_weights[ bp+rp*n_base_qp ] = radial_qw[rp] * base_qw[bp];
288  }
289  }
290 
291 }

Definition: inf_fe.h:660
template<unsigned int Dim, FEFamily T_radial, InfMapType T_map>
Point libMesh::InfFE< Dim, T_radial, T_map >::inverse_map ( const Elem *  elem,
const Point &  p,
const Real  tolerance = TOLERANCE,
const bool  secure = true,
const bool  interpolated = true 
)
static
Returns
the location (on the reference element) of the point p located in physical space. First, the location in the base face is computed. This requires inverting the (possibly nonlinear) transformation map in the base, so it is not trivial. The optional parameter tolerance defines how close is "good enough." The map inversion iteration computes the sequence , and the iteration is terminated when . Once the base face point is determined, the radial local coordinate is directly evaluated. If interpolated is true, the interpolated distance from the base element to the infinite element origin is used for the map in radial direction.

The number of iterations in the map inversion process.

Newton iteration loop.

237  // The form of the map and how we invert it depends
238  // on the dimension that we are in.
239  switch (Dim)
240  {
241 
242  //------------------------------------------------------------------
243  // 1D infinite element - no map inversion necessary
244  case 1:
245  {
246  break;
247  }

251  // 2D infinite element - 1D map inversion
252  //
253  // In this iteration scheme only search for the local coordinate
254  // in xi direction. Once xi is determined, the radial coordinate eta is
255  // uniquely determined, and there is no need to iterate in that direction.

261

272 
273  if (secure)
274  libmesh_assert_greater (G, 0.);
275 
276  const Real Ginv = 1./G;
277 
278  const Real dxidelta = dxi*delta;
279

282

284  }

288  //------------------------------------------------------------------
289  // 3D infinite element - 2D map inversion
290  //
291  // In this iteration scheme only search for the local coordinates
292  // in xi and eta direction. Once xi, eta are determined, the radial
293  // coordinate zeta may directly computed.
294  case 3:
295  {

299  const Point physical_guess = FE<2,LAGRANGE>::map (base_elem.get(), p);
300 
301  // How far our current iterate is from the actual point.
302  // const Point delta = physical_point - physical_guess;
303  const Point delta = intersection - physical_guess;
304 
305  const Point dxi = FE<2,LAGRANGE>::map_xi (base_elem.get(), p);
306  const Point deta = FE<2,LAGRANGE>::map_eta (base_elem.get(), p);
307 
308 
309  // For details on Newton's method see fe_map.C
310  const Real
311  G11 = dxi*dxi, G12 = dxi*deta,
312  G21 = dxi*deta, G22 = deta*deta;
313 
314 
315  const Real det = (G11*G22 - G12*G21);
316 
317  if (secure)
318  {
319  libmesh_assert_greater (det, 0.);
320  libmesh_assert_greater (std::abs(det), 1.e-10);
321  }
322 
323  const Real inv_det = 1./det;
324 
325  const Real
326  Ginv11 = G22*inv_det,
327  Ginv12 = -G12*inv_det,
328 
329  Ginv21 = -G21*inv_det,
330  Ginv22 = G11*inv_det;
331 
332 
333  const Real dxidelta = dxi*delta;
334  const Real detadelta = deta*delta;
335 
336  // compute only the first two coordinates.
337  dp(0) = (Ginv11*dxidelta + Ginv12*detadelta);
338  dp(1) = (Ginv21*dxidelta + Ginv22*detadelta);
339 
340  break;
341  }

343 
344 
345  // Some other dimension?
346  default:

348  } // end switch(Dim), dp now computed
349 
350 
351 
352  // determine the error in computing the local coordinates
353  // in the base: ||P_n+1 - P_n||
354  inverse_map_error = dp.size();
355 
356 
357  // P_n+1 = P_n + dp
358  p.add (dp);
359 
360 
361  // Increment the iteration count.
362  cnt++;
363 
364 
365  // Watch for divergence of Newton's
366  // method.
367  if (cnt > 10)
368  {
369  if (secure || !secure)
370  {
371  libmesh_here();

374  << cnt << " iterations:\n"

382  << std::endl;
383  }
384  }
385 
386  if (cnt > 20)
387  libmesh_error_msg("ERROR: Newton scheme FAILED to converge in " << cnt << " iterations!");
388 
389  // else
390  // {
391  // break;
392  // }
393  }
394  }

397 
398 
399  // 4.
400  //
401  // Now that we have the local coordinates in the base,
402  // compute the interpolated radial distance a(s,t) \p a_interpolated
403  if (interpolated)
404  switch (Dim)
405  {
406  case 1:
407  {
408  Real a_interpolated = Point( inf_elem->point(0)
409  - inf_elem->point(n_base_mapping_sf) ).size();
410 
411  p(0) = 1. - 2*a_interpolated/physical_point(0);
412 
413 #ifdef DEBUG
414  // the radial distance should always be >= -1.
415 
416  if (p(0)+1 < tolerance)
417  {
418  libmesh_here();
419  libMesh::err << "WARNING: radial distance p(0) is "
420  << p(0)
421  << std::endl;
422  }
423 #endif
424 
425  break;
426  }
427 
428 
429  case 2:
430  {
431  Real a_interpolated = 0.;
432 
433  // the distance between the origin and the physical point
434  const Real fp_o_dist = Point(o-physical_point).size();
435 
436  for (unsigned int i=0; i<n_base_mapping_sf; i++)
437  {
438  // the radial distance of the i-th base mapping point
439  const Real dist_i = Point( inf_elem->point(i)
440  - inf_elem->point(i+n_base_mapping_sf) ).size();
441  // weight with the corresponding shape function
442  a_interpolated += dist_i * FE<1,LAGRANGE>::shape(base_mapping_elem_type,
443  base_mapping_order,
444  i,
445  p);
446  }
447 
448  p(1) = 1. - 2*a_interpolated/fp_o_dist;
449 
450 #ifdef DEBUG
451  // the radial distance should always be >= -1.
452 
453  // if (p(1)+1 < tolerance)
454  // {
455  // libmesh_here();
456  // libMesh::err << "WARNING: radial distance p(1) is "
457  // << p(1)
458  // << std::endl;
459  // }
460 #endif
461 
462  break;
463  }
464 
465 
466  case 3:
467  {
468  Real a_interpolated = 0.;
469 
470 
471  // the distance between the origin and the physical point
472  const Real fp_o_dist = Point(o-physical_point).size();
473 
474  for (unsigned int i=0; i<n_base_mapping_sf; i++)
475  {
476  // the radial distance of the i-th base mapping point
477  const Real dist_i = Point( inf_elem->point(i)
478  - inf_elem->point(i+n_base_mapping_sf) ).size();
479 
480  // weight with the corresponding shape function
481  a_interpolated += dist_i * FE<2,LAGRANGE>::shape(base_mapping_elem_type,
482  base_mapping_order,
483  i,
484  p);
485 
486  }
487 
488  p(2) = 1. - 2*a_interpolated/fp_o_dist;
489 
490 #ifdef DEBUG
491 
492 
493  // the radial distance should always be >= -1.
494 
495  // if (p(2)+1 < tolerance)
496  // {
497  // libmesh_here();
498  // libMesh::err << "WARNING: radial distance p(2) is "
499  // << p(2)
500  // << std::endl;
501  // }
502 #endif
503 
504  break;
505  }
506 
507  default:
508  libmesh_error_msg("Unknown Dim = " << Dim);
509  } // end switch(Dim), p fully computed, including radial part
510 
511  // if we do not want the interpolated distance, then
512  // use newton iteration to get the actual distance
513  else
514  {
515  // distance from the physical point to the ifem origin
516  const Real fp_o_dist = Point(o-physical_point).size();
517 
518  // the distance from the intersection on the
519  // base to the origin
520  const Real a_dist = intersection.size();
521 
522  // element coordinate in radial direction
523  // here our first guess is 0.
524  Real v = 0.;
525 
526  // the order of the radial mapping
527  const Order radial_mapping_order (Radial::mapping_order());
528 
529  unsigned int cnt2 = 0;
530  inverse_map_error = 0.;
531 
532  // Newton iteration in 1-D
533  do
534  {
535  // the mapping in radial direction
536  // note that we only have two mapping functions in
537  // radial direction
538  const Real r = a_dist * InfFE<Dim,INFINITE_MAP,T_map>::eval (v, radial_mapping_order, 0)
539  + 2. * a_dist * InfFE<Dim,INFINITE_MAP,T_map>::eval (v, radial_mapping_order, 1);
540 
541  const Real dr = a_dist * InfFE<Dim,INFINITE_MAP,T_map>::eval_deriv (v, radial_mapping_order, 0)
542  + 2. * a_dist * InfFE<Dim,INFINITE_MAP,T_map>::eval_deriv (v, radial_mapping_order, 1);
543 
544  const Real G = dr*dr;
545  const Real Ginv = 1./G;
546 
547  const Real delta = fp_o_dist - r;
548  const Real drdelta = dr*delta;
549 
550  Real dp = Ginv*drdelta;
551 
552  // update the radial coordinate
553  v += dp;
554 
555  // note that v should be smaller than 1,
556  // since radial mapping function tends to infinity
557  if (v >= 1.)
558  v = .9999;
559 
560  inverse_map_error = std::fabs(dp);
561 
562  // increment iteration count
563  cnt2 ++;
564  if (cnt2 > 20)
565  libmesh_error_msg("ERROR: 1D Newton scheme FAILED to converge");
566 
567 
568  }
569  while (inverse_map_error > tolerance);
570 
571  switch (Dim)
572  {
573  case 1:
574  {
575  p(0) = v;
576  break;
577  }
578  case 2:
579  {
580  p(1) = v;
581  break;
582  }
583  case 3:
584  {
585  p(2) = v;
586  break;
587  }
588  default:
589  libmesh_error_msg("Unknown Dim = " << Dim);
590  }
591  }
592 
593  // If we are in debug mode do a sanity check. Make sure
594  // the point \p p on the reference element actually does
595  // map to the point \p physical_point within a tolerance.
596 #ifdef DEBUG
597  /*
598  const Point check = InfFE<Dim,T_radial,T_map>::map (inf_elem, p);
599  const Point diff = physical_point - check;
600 
601  if (diff.size() > tolerance)
602  {
603  libmesh_here();
604  libMesh::err << "WARNING: diff is "
605  << diff.size()
606  << std::endl;
607  }
608  */
609 #endif
610 
611 
612 
613 
614  // Stop logging the map inversion.
615  STOP_LOG("inverse_map()", "InfFE");
616 
617  return p;
618 }

736  (xi <= 1.+eps))
737  return true;
738 
739  return false;
740  }
741 
742 
743  case TRI3:
744  case TRI6:
745  {
746  // The reference triangle is isocoles
747  // and is bound by xi=0, eta=0, and xi+eta=1.
748  if ((xi >= 0.-eps) &&
749  (eta >= 0.-eps) &&
750  ((xi + eta) <= 1.+eps))
751  return true;
752 
753  return false;
754  }
755 
756 
757  case QUAD4:
758  case QUAD8:
759  case QUAD9:
760  {
761  // The reference quadrilateral element is [-1,1]^2.
762  if ((xi >= -1.-eps) &&
763  (xi <= 1.+eps) &&
764  (eta >= -1.-eps) &&
765  (eta <= 1.+eps))
766  return true;
767 
768  return false;
769  }
770 
771 
772  case TET4:
773  case TET10:
774  {
775  // The reference tetrahedral is isocoles
776  // and is bound by xi=0, eta=0, zeta=0,
777  // and xi+eta+zeta=1.
778  if ((xi >= 0.-eps) &&
779  (eta >= 0.-eps) &&
780  (zeta >= 0.-eps) &&
781  ((xi + eta + zeta) <= 1.+eps))
782  return true;
783 
784  return false;
785  }
786 
787 
788  case HEX8:
789  case HEX20:
790  case HEX27:
791  {
792  /*
793  if ((xi >= -1.) &&
794  (xi <= 1.) &&
795  (eta >= -1.) &&
796  (eta <= 1.) &&
797  (zeta >= -1.) &&
798  (zeta <= 1.))
799  return true;
800  */
801 
802  // The reference hexahedral element is [-1,1]^3.
803  if ((xi >= -1.-eps) &&
804  (xi <= 1.+eps) &&
805  (eta >= -1.-eps) &&
806  (eta <= 1.+eps) &&
807  (zeta >= -1.-eps) &&
808  (zeta <= 1.+eps))
809  {
810  // libMesh::out << "Strange Point:\n";
811  // p.print();
812  return true;
813  }
814 
815  return false;
816  }
817 
818  case PRISM6:
819  case PRISM15:
820  case PRISM18:
821  {
822  // Figure this one out...
823  // inside the reference triange with zeta in [-1,1]
824  if ((xi >= 0.-eps) &&
825  (eta >= 0.-eps) &&
826  (zeta >= -1.-eps) &&
827  (zeta <= 1.+eps) &&
828  ((xi + eta) <= 1.+eps))
829  return true;
830 
831  return false;
832  }
833 
834 
835  case PYRAMID5:
836  case PYRAMID13:
837  case PYRAMID14:
838  {
839  // Check that the point is on the same side of all the faces
840  // by testing whether:
841  //
842  // n_i.(x - x_i) <= 0
843  //
844  // for each i, where:
845  // n_i is the outward normal of face i,
846  // x_i is a point on face i.
847  if ((-eta - 1. + zeta <= 0.+eps) &&
848  ( xi - 1. + zeta <= 0.+eps) &&
849  ( eta - 1. + zeta <= 0.+eps) &&
850  ( -xi - 1. + zeta <= 0.+eps) &&
851  ( zeta >= 0.-eps))
852  return true;
853 
854  return false;
855  }
856 
857 #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_INFINITE_ELEMENTS
858  case INFHEX8:
859  {
860  // The reference infhex8 is a [-1,1]^3.
861  if ((xi >= -1.-eps) &&
862  (xi <= 1.+eps) &&
863  (eta >= -1.-eps) &&
864  (eta <= 1.+eps) &&
865  (zeta >= -1.-eps) &&
866  (zeta <= 1.+eps))
867  {
868  return true;
869  }
870  return false;
871  }
872 
873  case INFPRISM6:
874  {
875  // inside the reference triange with zeta in [-1,1]
876  if ((xi >= 0.-eps) &&
877  (eta >= 0.-eps) &&
878  (zeta >= -1.-eps) &&
879  (zeta <= 1.+eps) &&
880  ((xi + eta) <= 1.+eps))
881  {
882  return true;
883  }
884 
885  return false;
886  }
887 #endif
888 
889  default:
890  libmesh_error_msg("ERROR: Unknown element type " << t);
891  }
892 
893  // If we get here then the point is _not_ in the
894  // reference element. Better return false.
895 
896  return false;
897 }

template<unsigned int Dim, FEFamily T_radial, InfMapType T_map>
Real libMesh::InfFE< Dim, T_radial, T_map >::shape ( const FEType &  fet,
const ElemType  t,
const unsigned int  i,
const Point &  p 
)
static
Returns
the value of the shape function at point p. This method lets you specify the relevant data directly, and is therefore allowed to be static. Note that this class member is by far not as efficient as its counterpart in FE<Dim,T>, and is not employed in the reinit() cycle. Also note that this method does not return physically correct shapes, instead use compute_data(). The shape() methods should only be used for mapping.

template<unsigned int Dim, FEFamily T_radial, InfMapType T_map>
Real libMesh::InfFE< Dim, T_radial, T_map >::shape ( const FEType &  fet,
const Elem *  elem,
const unsigned int  i,
const Point &  p 
)
static
Returns
the value of the shape function at point p. This method lets you specify the relevant data directly, and is therefore allowed to be static. Note that this class member is not as efficient as its counterpart in FE<Dim,T>, and is not employed in the reinit() cycle. Also note that this method does not return physically correct shapes, instead use compute_data(). The shape() methods should only be used for mapping.
